public interface Vehicle {
    double getMileage();
    boolean hasPrice();
    double getPriceWhenNew();
}

public class CarDealer {
   // Amount that a car's value decreases per mile.
   double MILEAGE_FACTOR = 0.01;

   public double findValue(Vehicle vehicle, double defaultValue) {
       if(vehicle.hasPrice()){
           double mileage = vehicle.getMileage();
           // The Truck class implements Vehicle in another file.
           if(vehicle instanceof Truck){
              // Trucks last longer than cars, so mileage is less important.
               mileage /= 2.0;           
           }
           return vehicle.getPriceWhenNew() - mileage * MILEAGE_FACTOR;
       } else {
            return defaultValue;
       }
   }
}

/*

The main design problem in this code is the use of instanceof Truck (with a type-specific adjustment) inside findValue().
Why this is a problem
	•	The Vehicle interface is meant to provide a common abstraction for any vehicle (Car, Truck, etc.). 
        Code that works with Vehicle should treat all implementations uniformly via the interface methods (getMileage(), hasPrice(), getPriceWhenNew()).

	•	Checking the concrete type with instanceof and then applying special logic 
        (dividing mileage by 2 for trucks because “trucks last longer”) breaks polymorphism. 
        It means the CarDealer class has to “know” internal details about specific subclasses.

	•	This violates the Open-Closed Principle (open for extension, closed for modification): 
        If you later add a new vehicle type (e.g., Motorcycle, ElectricVan, SUV), you’ll probably need to modify findValue() 
        again to add more instanceof checks. That’s fragile and error-prone.

	•	It also hurts maintainability and readability — the valuation logic is scattered and hidden inside one method 
        instead of being encapsulated where it belongs (inside the vehicle classes themselves).

This is a classic code smell in object-oriented design. 
Using instanceof often signals that the class hierarchy or interface isn’t rich enough to express the varying behavior.

Better design (using polymorphism)
Move the mileage adjustment (or any type-specific valuation rule) into the Vehicle implementations themselves.
For example, add a method to the interface:

public interface Vehicle {
    double getMileage();
    boolean hasPrice();
    double getPriceWhenNew();

    // New method: how much mileage "counts" toward depreciation for this vehicle type
    double getEffectiveMileageForValuation();  // or getDepreciationFactor(), etc.
}

Then:
	•	Car implements it as: return getMileage();
	•	Truck implements it as: return getMileage() / 2.0; (or whatever the rule is)

Update findValue() to:

public double findValue(Vehicle vehicle, double defaultValue) {
    if (vehicle.hasPrice()) {
        double mileage = vehicle.getEffectiveMileageForValuation();  // no instanceof!
        return vehicle.getPriceWhenNew() - mileage * MILeAGE_FACTOR;
    } else {
        return defaultValue;
    }
}

This way:
	•	Behavior is encapsulated in the right place (the vehicle knows how it depreciates).
	•	Adding new vehicle types requires no changes to CarDealer.
	•	The code is cleaner, more extensible, and follows true OOP principles.

Other minor issues (not the main design flaw)
	•	The comment says “The Truck class implements Vehicle in another file” — that’s fine, 
        but relying on it with instanceof is exactly what makes the design brittle.

	•	Hard-coded magic number (/ 2.0) and constant MILEAGE_FACTOR could be improved, but they’re secondary.

	•	The method mixes concerns a bit (price check + valuation), but again, not the core problem.

The code “works correctly” right now because there are only two types, but it won’t scale well. 
This is the kind of issue interviewers or code reviewers love to point out to test understanding of polymorphism vs. type checking.

If this is from a quiz/interview, the expected answer is almost certainly “using instanceof instead of polymorphism” or 
“violation of the Open-Closed Principle / poor use of interface abstraction.”

*/

import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.*;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

enum TransactionType {
    DEPOSIT, WITHDRAWAL, TRANSFER
}

enum TransactionStatus {
    PENDING, SUCCESS, FAILED
}

enum AlertLevel {
    LOW, MEDIUM, HIGH
}

class Account {
    public int accountId;
    public double balance;
    public String owner;

    public Account(int accountId, String owner, double initialBalance) {
        this.accountId = accountId;
        this.owner = owner;
        this.balance = initialBalance;
    }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
    }

    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0 && balance >= amount) {
            balance -= amount;
            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Account{id=" + accountId + ", balance=" + balance + "}";
    }
}

class Transaction {
    public int txnId;
    public int fromAccountId;
    public int toAccountId;
    public double amount;
    public TransactionType type;
    public TransactionStatus status;
    public LocalDateTime timestamp;

    public Transaction(int txnId, int fromAccountId, int toAccountId, double amount, TransactionType type) {
        this.txnId = txnId;
        this.fromAccountId = fromAccountId;
        this.toAccountId = toAccountId;
        this.amount = amount;
        this.type = type;
        this.status = TransactionStatus.PENDING;
